1
00:00:04,754 --> 00:00:08,216
And what is spirit for the most part? 
That which cannot be seen.

2
00:00:08,356 --> 00:00:12,326
[Higher Taste | Deep Absorption]

3
00:00:12,553 --> 00:00:14,731
So sometimes Guru Mahārāj 
would joke and say,

4
00:00:14,731 --> 00:00:17,731
“We are devotees of the invisible.”

5
00:00:17,731 --> 00:00:19,261
[Laughing]

6
00:00:19,292 --> 00:00:22,422
Of that which you cannot see.

7
00:00:22,422 --> 00:00:26,910
What is beyond the grasp 
of ordinary people to see

8
00:00:26,910 --> 00:00:28,500
is clear to brahmans.

9
00:00:28,500 --> 00:00:31,901
They can see it very easily.

10
00:00:31,901 --> 00:00:34,901
Just as … I mean there are 
many examples of that.

11
00:00:34,901 --> 00:00:38,901
What writers see, 
other people don’t see.

12
00:00:38,915 --> 00:00:41,367
My photography teacher,

13
00:00:41,367 --> 00:00:46,137
she used to talk about 
putting on your ‘photographic eyes’.

14
00:00:46,137 --> 00:00:49,547
You have your camera at your side, 
but you go into your photographic mode.

15
00:00:49,560 --> 00:00:52,503
Sometimes she would start the class, 
she would look out of the window and go,

16
00:00:52,503 --> 00:00:57,483
“Well, looks like 
an F8 type of day.”

17
00:00:57,514 --> 00:01:00,441
She would start 
calling out apertures

18
00:01:00,441 --> 00:01:03,531
because she put on 
her ‘photographic eyes’.

19
00:01:03,531 --> 00:01:06,259
When in the Bhagavad-gītā,

20
00:01:06,259 --> 00:01:11,269
when Kṛṣṇa wants to reveal something 
extraordinarily spiritual to Arjuna,

21
00:01:11,269 --> 00:01:14,522
He’s saying, “You cannot see this 
with your present eyes.”

22
00:01:14,633 --> 00:01:18,703
So, divya chakṣu—“I am going 
to give you divine eyes

23
00:01:18,842 --> 00:01:20,562
so that you can see this,

24
00:01:20,562 --> 00:01:25,232
have a glimpse 
of infinite perspective.”

25
00:01:25,285 --> 00:01:28,105
Sticking with 
the photography example—

26
00:01:28,105 --> 00:01:32,245
there is short depth of field, 
and then there is

27
00:01:32,245 --> 00:01:35,895
a depth of field called ‘infinity’.

28
00:01:35,895 --> 00:01:39,872
In the short: what’s before you 
is in focus; everything else is blurred,

29
00:01:39,872 --> 00:01:43,553
and in an infinite depth of field
everything is in focus.

30
00:01:43,673 --> 00:01:48,070
So there is a perspective, 
infinite perspective

31
00:01:48,200 --> 00:01:51,711
that’s sought out by spiritually 
progressive people.

32
00:01:51,711 --> 00:01:56,009
A brahman who’s meditating,
lost in meditation,

33
00:01:56,009 --> 00:02:03,499
meaning, he is not very conscious
of the external world,

34
00:02:03,507 --> 00:02:07,519
he is deeply conscious 
of the internal world.

35
00:02:07,519 --> 00:02:10,506
And the noteworthy point is

36
00:02:10,506 --> 00:02:15,256
it’s on account of deep absorption 
in the internal world

37
00:02:15,256 --> 00:02:19,297
that he is not outer-directed.

38
00:02:19,297 --> 00:02:29,737
It’s not that by self-abnegation, 
by renouncing the objective world

39
00:02:29,738 --> 00:02:32,702
that he’s gone deep internally.

40
00:02:32,702 --> 00:02:38,452
That’s the conventional stereotype, 
but that’s not what is being underscored

41
00:02:38,452 --> 00:02:40,523
in the Bhāgavatam
or such literature.

42
00:02:40,523 --> 00:02:45,443
But rather they are saying, 
“On account of deep internal absorption

43
00:02:45,508 --> 00:02:52,508
the result is … the objective world 
becomes secondary and adjusted.”

44
00:02:52,532 --> 00:02:56,532
Like in Bhagavad-gītā, 
where Kṛṣṇa’s saying,

45
00:02:56,889 --> 00:03:03,109
viṣayā vinivartante 
nirāhārasya dehinaḥ

46
00:03:03,109 --> 00:03:07,649
rasa-varjaḿ raso 'py asya
paraḿ dṛṣṭvā nivartate 
[Bg: 2.59]

47
00:03:07,649 --> 00:03:11,739
“Arjuna”, they’re having discussion 
at this point about sense control,

48
00:03:11,961 --> 00:03:17,301
and He’s saying, “What’s the point 
of controlling your senses,

49
00:03:17,301 --> 00:03:23,291
if your mind is still obsessing 
over sense objects?”

50
00:03:23,401 --> 00:03:25,770
It’s actually 
a very interesting section.

51
00:03:25,770 --> 00:03:28,920
And in Prabhupād’s purport 
to that he says,

52
00:03:28,920 --> 00:03:32,130
“It’s better to be 
a sincere street sweeper

53
00:03:32,130 --> 00:03:34,920
than a charlatan meditator.”

54
00:03:36,113 --> 00:03:43,193
So He’s saying, “If the senses are controlled, 
but internally you’re dwelling on them,

55
00:03:43,255 --> 00:03:47,255
it’s like …” 
What do we say?

56
00:03:48,242 --> 00:03:52,272
“Intent is nine-tenths of the law.”

57
00:03:52,510 --> 00:03:54,242
We were speaking about this 
the other day.

58
00:03:54,242 --> 00:03:56,522
What qualifies something 
as karma—

59
00:03:56,522 --> 00:03:59,512
the mind is the seat of karma—

60
00:03:59,512 --> 00:04:03,682
is not as much the action, 
but the internal motive.

61
00:04:03,682 --> 00:04:06,542
Just like in a criminal trial,

62
00:04:06,566 --> 00:04:11,518
when they have to …
It’s clear … both sides agree, let’s say,

63
00:04:11,518 --> 00:04:14,773
both sides agree
to what happened.

64
00:04:14,773 --> 00:04:19,822
The defence and the … 
What’s the other side?

65
00:04:19,822 --> 00:04:23,102
The prosecuting, 
the prosecuting attorney.

66
00:04:23,102 --> 00:04:25,272
They both agree 
to what happened,

67
00:04:25,289 --> 00:04:29,289
but what’s going 
to determine culpability

68
00:04:29,289 --> 00:04:31,489
is motive.

69
00:04:31,502 --> 00:04:34,752
What was the person 
thinking at that time?

70
00:04:34,753 --> 00:04:38,773
That’s going to make
all the difference.

71
00:04:38,804 --> 00:04:42,521
So in the Gītā Kṛṣṇa says,

72
00:04:42,521 --> 00:04:49,551
“Just trying to renounce 
the objective world will be …

73
00:04:49,551 --> 00:04:51,681
will prove futile

74
00:04:51,681 --> 00:04:57,421
in really subduing the senses.
Or being misled by the senses.”

75
00:04:57,421 --> 00:04:59,062
He’s saying, “But rather

76
00:04:59,062 --> 00:05:04,382
rasa-varjaṁ raso ’py asya 
paraṁ dṛṣṭvā nivartate.”

77
00:05:04,382 --> 00:05:07,874
We’re back to the word ‘rishi’ 
is encoded there.

78
00:05:07,954 --> 00:05:11,184
Paraḿ dṛṣṭvā—
‘superior experience’.

79
00:05:11,190 --> 00:05:14,296
In the presence 
of a superior experience

80
00:05:14,296 --> 00:05:18,436
automatically
inferior experience retreats.

81
00:05:18,796 --> 00:05:21,506
That’s the way.
That’s the best.

82
00:05:21,530 --> 00:05:25,706
A higher taste—
lower taste vanishes.

83
00:05:25,736 --> 00:05:33,539
‘Drishtva’, ‘rishi’, ‘drishi’—those 
who are seeing, experiencing the truth,

84
00:05:33,539 --> 00:05:37,499
they’re not outer-directed.

85
00:05:37,509 --> 00:05:42,172
So sometimes people will think, 
“Well, these ancient civilizations

86
00:05:43,542 --> 00:05:46,182
and cultures were so advanced,

87
00:05:46,182 --> 00:05:51,896
how come they appear 
to be technologically primitive?”

88
00:05:51,972 --> 00:05:56,542
Well, one way of looking at it 
is they were so inner-directed

89
00:05:56,542 --> 00:06:02,171
that they only put 
the minimum effort in outer things.

90
00:06:02,171 --> 00:06:08,741
The old saying 
“Simple living, high thinking.”

91
00:06:08,768 --> 00:06:14,448
They didn’t want to complicate
unnecessarily their outer lives

92
00:06:14,671 --> 00:06:16,601
is one way of looking at it.

